english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of the People's Joy
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Where Cloud Peak stretches eastward through mountain valleys, many waters converge into a great stream, flowing through the lands of Hapcheon and Chogyè before joining the river. Across the borderlands between these two districts, fields open wide and mountains stand revealed—their clear and distant beauty has long been beloved. Yet for years the passage of travelers knew no shelter where such beauty could be shared.

    In the second year of the Hongwu era, the esteemed Li Renshi, having served as magistrate of Yingde with great distinction, was promoted to oversee Chogyè. Within months of his arrival, his governance brought fairness to disputes and order to the people. The following year saw corruption swept away, affairs conducted with merit, and harvests abundant. Thus he consulted with the people and borrowed their labor for ten days. They felled timber and floated it downstream to the work site. There, beside where the pavilion would stand, a kiln master was firing tiles. Li arranged for the tiles to be baked there, providing meals as payment—thereby saving both labor and expense. Setting dates and directing idle hands to work, they began that autumn in the seventh month and completed the pavilion within days.

    Three chambers were built—rooms for weary travelers to rest, and open galleries for viewing the landscape. The weary journey of passing officials could find solace here, their hardship repaid by the splendor that surrounds. Yet this pavilion was never meant merely for comfort. From here, the magistrate receives and bids farewell to guests, encourages the people's livelihood. To the north rises Mount Gaya, to the south Mount Wueol. Mount Gap stands to the left, Mount Hwang to the right—verdant peaks converge as if upon one's own seat. The waters turn past sheer cliffs to the west, embrace high banks to the east, their spray dancing like jewels upon the table before us.

    Mist hovers over the pools, moonlight plays on sandbars, grasses fringe the water's edge, flowers bloom upon the banks. Through all four seasons the landscape transforms, and the magistrate's joy knows no end. Here the farmer sings, the fisherman plays his flute, the traveler hums—joy and delight never depart from beneath these eaves.

    Li finds his pleasure in mountain and water, in the people's happiness. He comes at dawn and forgets to return at dusk. A few miles west of the pavilion, the road narrows dangerously between sheer cliffs, rising and falling hundreds of feet—travelers must hurry breathlessly through, running hundred paces before reaching safety. All who pass between east and west must rest here. What greater joy could there be?

    Mengzi taught: "One who finds joy in the people's joy shall find the people joyful in return." So Li finds his joy in this pavilion and shares it with his people, and they rejoice in his joy. Even the flowing waters and drifting clouds seem to have found their rightful place. Ah, how far the ripples of joy extend!

    Recently, Li requested that I name this pavilion and write its record. I once studied at the local academy and know well that Li's benevolence is sufficient to win hearts, and his wisdom sufficient to serve the people. Therefore I have named it the Pavilion of the People's Joy. And seeing how the people joyfully labored to raise these walls, I write this record with equal joy.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Cloud Peak (雲峯) refers to a prominent geographical landmark in the region of Chogyè in present-day South Korea.
  - key: ''
    value: The Hongwu era and the year mentioned (癸酉, 甲戌) correspond to the early years of the Chosŏn Dynasty in Korean history.
  - key: ''
    value: Mount Gaya, Wueol, Gap, and Hwang are all real mountains visible from Chogyè, serving as landmarks that orient the reader to the pavilion's strategic location.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Mengzi (Mencius) invokes classical Confucian philosophy to elevate the magistrate's virtues and the pavilion's purpose beyond mere shelter.
